<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="105" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="105">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="105">
Rather rare in Europe but more common in the Far East of Russia (
<bibRefCitation author="Shatalkin, AI" journalOrPublisher="Trudy Zoologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR" pageId="18" pageNumber="113" pagination="69 - 136" title="Obzor gribnykh mukh (Diptera, Platypezidae) fauny SSSR. [A review of the ﬂat-footed ﬂies (Diptera, Platypezidae) of USSR]." volume="23" year="1985">Shatalkin 1985</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler, PJ" journalOrPublisher="Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica Volume 36, Brill, Leiden, Boston, Koeln" pageId="17" pageNumber="112" title="The flat-footed flies (Diptera: Opetiidae and Platypezidae) of Europe." year="2001">Chandler 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Its larvae develop in several species of 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Polyporaceae" genus="Polyporus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Polyporus" order="Polyporales" pageId="10" pageNumber="105" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Polyporus</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sevcik, J" journalOrPublisher="Slezske zemske muzeum, Opava" pageId="19" pageNumber="114" title="Czech and Slovak Diptera associated with fungi." year="2010">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ševčík">Sevcik</normalizedToken>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
). Adults occur in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="VI–VII">VI-VII</normalizedToken>
and IX.
</paragraph>
